cells.data:
Trivial constructor, standard layout => POD
[descriptions](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/mt767760.aspx)

Taking the example code:
```c++
struct BasicStruct
{
    int foo;
    double bar;
};

struct DerivedStruct : BasicStruct
{
    int vald;
    double bard;
};

struct AbstractStruct
{
    int foo;
    double bar;
    virtual void do_nothing() = 0;
};

struct PrivateStruct
{
    int foo;
  private:
    double bar;
};

struct NontrivialStruct
{
    int foo;
    double bar;
    NontrivialStruct(int i);
};
```

and copying the output using `print_pynode`:
```py
items = {k: set(v) for k,v in classes.items()}
basic = items.pop('BasicStruct')
for k,v in items.items():
    print(k, " has:", ",".join(sorted(v - basic)))
    print(k, " is missing:", ",".join(sorted(basic - v)))
```
yields
```
PrivateStruct  has: previousSibling
PrivateStruct  is missing: 
AbstractStruct  has: abstracts,previousSibling
AbstractStruct  is missing: has_default_constructor
DerivedStruct  has: allbases,baselist,bases,previousSibling,privatebaselist,protectedbaselist
DerivedStruct  is missing: 
NontrivialStruct  has: allocate:has_constructor,allocate:public_constructor,previousSibling
NontrivialStruct  is missing: allocate:default_constructor,has_default_constructor,nextSibling
```

Thus it should be easy to give default struct accessibility for everything but types with private data.
